---
title: Nx vs Blacksmith
description: Blacksmith replaces GitHub Actions runners with faster machines. Nx reduces how much work runs at all with affected detection, remote task caching, and dynamic distribution. Compare them, or run both together.
filter: 'type:Guides'
sidebar:
  label: Nx vs Blacksmith
---

Blacksmith makes your CI machines faster. Nx makes less work run on them, through affected detection, remote caching, and task distribution. Run both and you get cheaper minutes and fewer of them.

## What is Nx?

Nx is a monorepo platform: a task-running CLI, remote caching, distributed CI across machines, e2e test splitting, flaky-task handling, self-healing CI, and editor integration, one system rather than separate products. It layers onto whatever CI provider you already run.

## What is Blacksmith?

Blacksmith is a drop-in replacement for GitHub Actions runners. It moves your jobs onto faster bare-metal machines with accelerated dependency and Docker layer caches, billed per minute with no annual commitment.

## Quick takeaway

Blacksmith and Nx Cloud work on different layers. Blacksmith is a runner provider: swap the `runs-on` label and every job runs on a faster machine. Nx Cloud is a task-distribution orchestrator: it reads your project graph to skip unaffected tasks, replay cached results, and spread the rest across machines. Blacksmith runners are standard GitHub Actions runners, so an Nx workspace can run its CI on Blacksmith with Nx Cloud on top, cheaper minutes and fewer of them. Blacksmith gives a one-time raw-speed bump, and past that there is little more to squeeze. Nx keeps compounding: task distribution, flaky re-runs, and task-level caching, plus it drops the manual matrix and sharding that become the real maintenance cost once simple parallelism stops scaling.

